<DOC><DOCNO> AP890414-0086 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0901EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Wedtech-Moreno     04-14 0359</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Wedtech-Moreno,0371</SECOND><HEAD>Former Wedtech Exec Gets 18-Month Prison Term</HEAD><BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former Wedtech Corp. executive who admittedstealing millions of dollars from the now-defunct defensecontractor and bribing several public officials could be out ofjail by November, prosecutors say.   Mario Moreno, a key government witness at the racketeering trialof ex-Rep. Mario Biaggi, was sentenced at a secret court sessionThursday to 18 months in prison for conspiring to bribe publicofficials and other corruption charges.   Moreno, 47, former vice chairman of Wedtech, could have beensentenced to 15 years in prison and $750,000 in fines. He has beenin custody since November and will be eligible for parole afterserving two-thirds of his sentence, or one year, authorities said.   The sentencing by U.S. District Judge Charles E. Stewart was notannounced by prosecutors until after it was completed.   In two weeks on the witness stand at the Biaggi trial, Morenoadmitted he and three other Wedtech officials paid millions ofdollars in bribes to obtain government contracts for Wedtech.   Biaggi, 71, was sentenced to eight years in prison in Novemberafter he was convicted of turning Wedtech into a racketeeringenterprise that paid millions in bribes and kickbacks.   Five co-defendants also were convicted of various charges withBiaggi, who began serving a prison sentence this week on anunrelated bribery case.   In a four-page letter assistant U.S. attorney Edward J.M. Littlesent to Stewart on Tuesday and made public Thursday, the prosecutordetailed the extent of Moreno's cooperation.   It said he supplied information that led to the conviction ofBiaggi, Biaggi's son, the former commander of the New York NationalGuard, former Bronx Borough President Stanley Simon, former WhiteHouse aide Lyn Nofziger, the former head of the Small BusinessAdministration's New York office, two former Maryland legislatorsand several others.   Former Attorney General Edwin Meese III was investigated butnever charged with any wrongdoing in the Wedtech scandal, althougha special prosecutor criticized Meese's ethical decisions in thecase.   Two former Meese business associates are slated to go on trialnext week on racketeering charges.</TEXT></DOC>